text=:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild%0a:Essential: {Category.LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild$:essential}%0a:Title: Linguistic Discrimination Against Th-stopping%0a:Author: samV%0a:Section: C%0a:Completed: 24.04.2021 - 21:15%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a----%0a%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210505-021907-450910#%0a* [-04.05.2021 - 19:19-] || TA_lili marked as complete%0a#foxend 210505-021907-450910#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0aSummary: \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aFrom Quora, an example of discrimination against a common occurance of AAVE grammar%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aQuora is rich with questions that are ignorant of linguistics and the legitimacy of "different" accents/dialects. I came across this especially hostile example, in which the author and several responders problematically lambast the use of "da" instead of "the".%0a%0a%3chttps://www.quora.com/Do-people-who-say-da-instead-of-the-ever-consider-going-for-speech-therapy/>%0a%0aThe target of this thread comes from Th-stopping of the word-initial [รฐ], instead realizing the dental fricative as the alveolar stop [d]. This is observed in the grammars of several dialects of English, and prominently in AAVE. AAVE is often the target of linguistic discrimination from those who hold prescriptive beliefs that AAVE constitutes a less proper version of English. %0aThe original asker of this thread suggests that people who speak this way should consider speech therapy. One answerer replies that these speakers only do so out of ingrained laziness. The other answer comes from a linguist who disagrees with the question's problematic premise, but another user replies to this answer that these speakers will be received by general society as mentally deficient, and so the usage must be discouraged to uphold workplace standards of proper language. Given how these comments are phrased, it's clear enough that this criticism isn't supposed to be just about "da" versus "the", but rather about all of AAVE / "improper" accents without explicitly naming them.%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:GradedBy: TA_lili:)
